            "answer_text": "There are not many descendants of the Polish refugees in Iran. During the war the huge majority of the 120 thousand people who arrived from the soviet gulags joined the newly forming Polish army and went on to Palestine, Egypt and then to fight in Italy. Most healthy Polish children over the age of 14 left Iran together with the Polish army. Some of them pretended to be older than they were in order to enrol. They had no birth certificates that could be checked.  Of the ones who stayed in Iran there were about 2500 young children and a few hundred women, too weak or too ill to join the army. By 1946 the children had been relocated to New Zealand, Australia, Canada, the US and South Africa, together with most of their carers. A few hundred women stayed dispersed in a few places in Iran. By the mid 1950s the numbers dropped, most of them were going back to Poland. By 1958 only 10 with Polish citizenship were registered by the authorities. They had married Iranian men, started families and decided to stay. Years later attempts were made to find out more about them. In 2007 a documentary was made in Polish: \u2018Kres podr\u00f3\u017cy \u2013 polskie \u015blady w Iranie\u2019 (End of the journey \u2013 Polish traces in Iran). 4 women contributed their stories: Helena Stelmach, Aniela Wojciechowska, Maria Bojdan, Olga Fazel. Helena Stelmach and Aniela Wojciechowska remained Christian. They were attending Christian Armenian churches, they celebrated Christmas and Easter at home, as well as other Christian holidays, although their husbands and their children were Muslim. Helena Stelmach, who gave the interview in perfect Polish , had lived in an exclusively Iranian environment since the war. It\u2019samazing not to forget the language after all the years. The only time the women occasionally met up was at some celebrations at the Polish embassy in Tehran. In Helena\u2019s words, she had deep love for Poland but also for Iran, which she considered her home. She passed down her love for Poland to her son, Reza Nikpour, who has written an illustrated publication in Persian \u201cPoland and Iran\u201d, tracing links between the two countries over centuries. The main chapter is dedicated to ww2. It was published by the Polish embassy in Tehran. Reza and Alireza Dalatshahim are trying to set up a Polish -Iranian Friendly Society. Reza\u2019s mother, Helena, died on 28th of April 2017, aged 86. She was the last Polish person remaining in Iran after ww2. Polish people were very well received in Iran during the war. When they recovered from the gulag deprivations they left to fight some ww2 battles. The 3500 Polish graves in Iran come from the early months, mainly 1942, when the people arrived exhausted, weak and sick with typhus and TB. The deaths were the consequence of the years in the gulags. Very few graves come from the time after the war. Cemetary in Tehran:   ",
